WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.640 --> 00:00:09.390
&gt;&gt;presenter: This talk is part of the Authors@Google
of the Health@Google series. We'll have a

00:00:09.390 --> 00:00:16.110
lot of time at the end for questions and there's
a mic here.

00:00:16.110 --> 00:00:23.339
So, I'm very pleased to welcome today, Gary
Taubes, who is a contributing correspondent

00:00:23.339 --> 00:00:31.609
for Science Magazine. His work has appeared
in the New York Times, the Atlantic, the Esquire.

00:00:31.609 --> 00:00:40.399
His work has also been included in The Best
of The Best American Science Writing and also

00:00:40.399 --> 00:00:47.120
has received three Science in the Society
Journalism awards from the National Association

00:00:47.120 --> 00:00:48.670
of Science Writers.

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:56.390
He's the author, also, of 'Good Calories,
Bad Calories' that I'm sure many of you know

00:00:56.390 --> 00:01:11.780
about. And currently, he is the Robert Wood
Johnson Foundation investigator in health

00:01:11.780 --> 00:01:18.200
policy research at the University of Berkeley.

00:01:18.200 --> 00:01:19.200
So, with this, we'll have Gary Taubes talk
about his latest book.

00:01:19.200 --> 00:01:20.200
[applause]

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:21.860
&gt;&gt;Gary Taubes: Thank you very much. This book
is basically -- 'Good Calories, Bad Calories'

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.970
took me about five years to write and was
500 pages long.

00:01:24.970 --> 00:01:29.580
This is the screen I used to use for this
talk and I had written that book hoping to

00:01:29.580 --> 00:01:32.310
get both the lay readers and to the public
health authorities around the country and

00:01:32.310 --> 00:01:38.430
the medical research community. 'Cause the
goal of these books are to convince people

00:01:38.430 --> 00:01:43.160
that--I mean, it's almost a cliché--but that
our fundamental understanding of why we get

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:48.789
fat, of obesity, is completely incorrect and
that a new paradigm is in order.

00:01:48.789 --> 00:01:55.759
And that Google should change the foods that
they're serving at their wonderful, healthy,

00:01:55.759 --> 00:02:00.870
low-fat cafes. So, after 'Good Calories, Bad
Calories' came out, I wrote 'Why We Get Fat',

00:02:00.870 --> 00:02:07.039
in effect, to make it the kind of airplane-reading
version of 'Good Calories, Bad Calories' for

00:02:07.039 --> 00:02:08.979
people who don't have the time.

00:02:08.979 --> 00:02:12.950
I got a lot of emails from people, from doctors,
who asked me if I could write a book that

00:02:12.950 --> 00:02:16.810
their patients could read, from patients who
asked me if I could write a book that their

00:02:16.810 --> 00:02:18.730
doctors would read.

00:02:18.730 --> 00:02:19.930
[laughter]

00:02:19.930 --> 00:02:25.810
So, in this lecture, 'Why We Get Fat' is actually
based on the lecture. So, once you've seen

00:02:25.810 --> 00:02:32.819
this, you don't actually have to read the
book. Let me see if this works a little. That's

00:02:32.819 --> 00:02:33.819
better.

00:02:33.819 --> 00:02:35.970
This is just background. You know there's
an obesity epidemic in the works. I'm not

00:02:35.970 --> 00:02:40.970
gonna go over it because, as usual, I'm probably
gonna run a little long on this talk. The

00:02:40.970 --> 00:02:46.739
obesity epidemic goes along with the diabetes
epidemic. Diabetes diagnoses have tripled

00:02:46.739 --> 00:02:49.400
in the past 30 years in the United States.

00:02:49.400 --> 00:02:58.990
And let's see if this. [pause] Diabetes, obesity
are associated with a host of chronic diseases

00:02:58.990 --> 00:03:03.409
that are known as metabolic diseases, which
include fatty liver disease, atherosclerosis,

00:03:03.409 --> 00:03:09.319
hypertension, stroke, cancer, asthma, sleep
apnea, osteoarthritis, neural degeneration.

00:03:09.319 --> 00:03:15.349
Actually, Alzheimer's disease is a disease
that's now associated with what's called insulin

00:03:15.349 --> 00:03:17.120
resistance in obesity.

00:03:17.120 --> 00:03:23.910
And one of the subtexts of the talk I'm gonna
give today is that the conventional wisdom

00:03:23.910 --> 00:03:31.049
is that as we get fatter, that increases the
risk of all these diseases and the fundamental

00:03:31.049 --> 00:03:32.049
problem is us getting fatter.

00:03:32.049 --> 00:03:36.519
And I'm gonna suggest that the same foods,
the same thing that makes us fat, also causes

00:03:36.519 --> 00:03:42.319
these diseases. So, it's a fundamentally different
causality.

00:03:42.319 --> 00:03:48.269
So the question we want is why do we get fat?
Obvious question. And the officials answers

00:03:48.269 --> 00:03:53.799
are, "Obesity occurs when a person consumes
more calories from food than he or she burns."

00:03:53.799 --> 00:03:58.689
"Overweight is the result of a caloric imbalance
and is mediated by genetics and health." That's

00:03:58.689 --> 00:04:00.560
what the old Surgeon General and the NIH tells
us.

00:04:00.560 --> 00:04:05.430
So how many people in this room actually believe
this and think it's meaningful? That's not

00:04:05.430 --> 00:04:06.430
bad.

00:04:06.430 --> 00:04:11.090
You know, I gave this talk at Tufts a couple
weeks ago to the nutrition department. And

00:04:11.090 --> 00:04:15.560
the Tufts people have been behind every dietary
guidelines for the past 20 years. And I asked

00:04:15.560 --> 00:04:18.780
how many people believe this and nobody--literally,
nobody--raised their hand. And then I said,

00:04:18.780 --> 00:04:23.100
"Are you kidding? 'Cause if you don't, I can
leave." And then everybody raised their hand.

00:04:23.100 --> 00:04:27.360
And then after the talk, they said, "Well,
we don't really believe it."

00:04:27.360 --> 00:04:30.800
So here's a conventional wisdom: "Energy in
is greater than energy out." And that's why

00:04:30.800 --> 00:04:38.320
we get fat. We take in more energy than we
consume. We overeat and the excess calories

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:41.890
go to our fat tissue. You hear about this
in a lot of different ways.

00:04:41.890 --> 00:04:47.820
In the medical literature, they'll refer to
"over nutrition". "Positive energy balance"

00:04:47.820 --> 00:04:51.920
is another way to phrase it. And often, virtually
every article you read on obesity, they'll

00:04:51.920 --> 00:04:55.290
say, "Obesity is a disorder of energy balance."

00:04:55.290 --> 00:04:58.940
And when they say that, what they mean is
we take in more calories than we consume and

00:04:58.940 --> 00:05:00.160
that's why we get fat.

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:06.950
So here's the general image of what's going
on here. And what you wanna do when we talk

00:05:06.950 --> 00:05:12.000
about this, one of the key things you wanna
do in any science is explain the observations.

00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:15.920
So we have this observation of an obesity
epidemic and we want to explain it by our

00:05:15.920 --> 00:05:19.790
hypothesis, which is that we take in more
calories than we expend.

00:05:19.790 --> 00:05:24.030
And the way it's been done over the years
is that the idea is "increased prosperity."

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:29.490
This is what Marion Nestle, a New York University
nutritionist, wrote in 'Science', "As we get

00:05:29.490 --> 00:05:34.950
richer, more food becomes available. We have
less reason to become physically active."

00:05:34.950 --> 00:05:38.960
That food's on every street corner. You don't
have to work to get it.

00:05:38.960 --> 00:05:45.040
And so we get fatter and fatter. Kelly Brownell,
a Yale University psychologist, used, coined

00:05:45.040 --> 00:05:50.570
the term "toxic environment," which is an
environment that promotes overeating and sedentary

00:05:50.570 --> 00:05:55.840
behavior. And so physical activity, and as
Kelly put it, he said, "Cheese curls and French

00:05:55.840 --> 00:05:59.880
fries,[audience chuckles] fast food joints
are as much a part of our environment as trees

00:05:59.880 --> 00:06:05.400
and clouds. Mothers keep their kids home from
school. We sit in front of computer screens

00:06:05.400 --> 00:06:07.910
all day long and video games and television."

00:06:07.910 --> 00:06:13.840
So a lot of reasons to eat too much, not enough
reason to burn it off. And the question we

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:19.250
wanna know -- here's the hypothesis: increased
prosperity leads to overeating--energy in

00:06:19.250 --> 00:06:24.160
is greater than energy out-- and that leads
to obesity and the obesity epidemic. And what

00:06:24.160 --> 00:06:29.371
we wanna know is, is this true? 'Cause this
is a science and in science, this is a hypothesis.

00:06:29.371 --> 00:06:34.330
So you just ask a question. Is this true?
Does it explain the observations?

00:06:34.330 --> 00:06:38.120
When I'm lecturing to nutrition departments
and obesity research departments, I often

00:06:38.120 --> 00:06:42.770
wanna piss them off in the beginning. It's
part of my nature. And I'll say, "Let's pretend

00:06:42.770 --> 00:06:49.020
this is a science for a second [audience chuckles]
and see if this can actually explain the observations."

00:06:49.020 --> 00:06:53.410
There are a lot of observations out there,
but they're less than obvious. They're not

00:06:53.410 --> 00:06:57.580
-- right now, we know we've got McDonalds
on every street corner. We know a lot of people

00:06:57.580 --> 00:07:00.330
watch television. And we know a lot of people
are getting heavier.

00:07:00.330 --> 00:07:05.420
So we put them all together, these associations,
and we say. "That's the cause". But we could

00:07:05.420 --> 00:07:13.811
find populations that didn't have all these,
this toxic environment as we define it, and

00:07:13.811 --> 00:07:16.740
we could look to see if the obesity existed
there.

00:07:16.740 --> 00:07:21.730
And one of the underlying contexts here, one
of my underlying hypothesis, and also of any

00:07:21.730 --> 00:07:26.800
science, the underlying principles is Occam's
Razor. So we should find the simplest possible

00:07:26.800 --> 00:07:27.800
hypothesis.

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:33.330
So we're gonna work from the hypothesis of
whatever makes any population fat is what

00:07:33.330 --> 00:07:36.720
makes our population fat, until we have to
change it.

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:41.970
So, here we have a photo. This young woman,
or middle-aged woman, was known as 'Fat Louisa'.

00:07:41.970 --> 00:07:47.900
This photo was taken in 1902. And Fat Louisa
was a Pima Indian. And the Pima live on the

00:07:47.900 --> 00:07:52.250
Gila River reservation. Now, it's the Gila
River reservation, south of Phoenix, Arizona.

00:07:52.250 --> 00:07:57.620
What's little-known about the Pima is today,
they are the poster children for obesity and

00:07:57.620 --> 00:08:02.780
diabetes in the United States cause they have,
conceivably, the highest risk of any population.

00:08:02.780 --> 00:08:08.510
In the 17th, 18th, 19th Century, they were
the most affluent Native American tribe. They

00:08:08.510 --> 00:08:13.940
were hunters and gatherers. They hunted in
the nearby mountains. They fished in the Gila

00:08:13.940 --> 00:08:24.960
River. They raised sheep--not sheep--cattle,
pigs. They had warehouses full of food available

00:08:24.960 --> 00:08:26.081
in the 1840s.

00:08:26.081 --> 00:08:31.810
When the first US Army Battalion moved to
the Pima territory on the San Jose Trail,

00:08:31.810 --> 00:08:38.241
they reported that the Pima had this incredible
amount of food available. And they were all

00:08:38.241 --> 00:08:44.050
lean and sprightly. And by 1849, gold was
discovered in California.

00:08:44.050 --> 00:08:51.460
And over the next 20 years, 20 to 60 thousand
49ers went west to the Pima territory and

00:08:51.460 --> 00:08:55.700
the US government asked the Pima to feed them,
which they did, and protect them from the

00:08:55.700 --> 00:09:00.960
hostile tribes farther West. And then by the
1870s, 1880s, Mexican Americans and Anglo

00:09:00.960 --> 00:09:05.540
Americans started moving into the Pima territory
and they overhunted the nearby mountains.

00:09:05.540 --> 00:09:10.430
They diverted the Gila River water to irrigate
their own fields, and the Pima went into what

00:09:10.430 --> 00:09:14.860
they called the Years of Famine, which lasted
for 20 or 30 years.

00:09:14.860 --> 00:09:24.490
And by 1902, when Frank Rosso, a Harvard anthropologist
came to live with the Pima and wrote the Seminole

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:29.200
text on the Pima Indians, they were living
on a reservation. They were struggling as

00:09:29.200 --> 00:09:36.830
farmers to survive, and it was [pause] it
was Rosso who took the photo of Fat Louisa

00:09:36.830 --> 00:09:41.250
on the right. And he said many old people
in the tribe, unlike the classical image of

00:09:41.250 --> 00:09:47.070
the strong, buff Native American, many old
people in the tribe were actually obese and

00:09:47.070 --> 00:09:48.070
overweight.

00:09:48.070 --> 00:09:52.740
And this was an observation that was seconded
a few years later by Alex Hrdlicka, who was

00:09:52.740 --> 00:09:58.660
the physician-anthropologist who went on to
become the curator of the Smithsonian, Department

00:09:58.660 --> 00:10:03.820
of Physical Anthropology. So, the point about
the Pima was that they went from being affluent

00:10:03.820 --> 00:10:10.740
in the 1840s -- that drawing was actually
made in 1851 -- to poor in 1902. And they

00:10:10.740 --> 00:10:15.050
went through 30 years of famine in the middle.
And 30 years of famine, you could think of

00:10:15.050 --> 00:10:20.280
as 30 years of being on a diet. And they should
have been leaner, right? 'Cause our hypothesis

00:10:20.280 --> 00:10:26.940
says if poverty leading to prosperity causes
obesity, not prosperity leading to poverty.

00:10:26.940 --> 00:10:32.210
And yet, in the early 19th Century, we have
a high level of obesity observed by two separate

00:10:32.210 --> 00:10:38.360
anthropologists living with the tribe. If
this was the only example, we could probably

00:10:38.360 --> 00:10:43.380
toss it and assume something else was going
on. But there are a lot of examples of obesity

00:10:43.380 --> 00:10:47.840
in what we would call "non-toxic environments."

00:10:47.840 --> 00:10:51.760
And one of the things that sort of pissed
me off doing my research for 'Good Calories,

00:10:51.760 --> 00:10:57.610
Bad Calories', which took five years, is you
only had to go to look for them to find them.

00:10:57.610 --> 00:11:02.190
And yet, the obesity research community hadn't
bothered 'cause they had settled on their

00:11:02.190 --> 00:11:06.500
hypothesis. It's all about overeating. It's
all about taking in too many calories. It's

00:11:06.500 --> 00:11:11.310
all about fast food joints. And so they never
looked. If you go look, you'll find a lot

00:11:11.310 --> 00:11:17.570
of different populations. The Sioux on the
South Dakota Crow Creek Reservation, in 1928

00:11:17.570 --> 00:11:22.850
-- this was a study done by two University
of Chicago economists.

00:11:22.850 --> 00:11:29.030
And this, this population was so poor that
you could use it. You could put it in the

00:11:29.030 --> 00:11:32.480
dictionary next to the definition of "dirt
poor." They lived four to eight people per

00:11:32.480 --> 00:11:38.240
room. Something like 15 families with 32 children
on the reservation were living only on bread

00:11:38.240 --> 00:11:44.851
and coffee. There were no bathrooms. There's
no plumbing. They had to get water from the

00:11:44.851 --> 00:11:51.010
river. And yet, 40 percent of the women, 25
percent of the men, and 10 percent of the

00:11:51.010 --> 00:11:55.260
children were distinctly fat. And 20 percent
of the women, 25 percent of the men, and 25

00:11:55.260 --> 00:12:00.779
percent of the children were distinctly thin.
And there were definite signs of malnutrition.

00:12:00.779 --> 00:12:07.230
The economists documented all kinds of deficiency
diseases among these Native Americans. And

00:12:07.230 --> 00:12:14.190
this combination of obesity and malnutrition,
or under nutrition, existing in the same population

00:12:14.190 --> 00:12:21.560
is an observation I'm gonna come back to shortly
-- many times, in fact. OK, African Americans

00:12:21.560 --> 00:12:28.090
in Charleston, South Carolina in 1959. Thirty
percent of the women are obese and 18 percent

00:12:28.090 --> 00:12:31.050
of the men. Family incomes are nine to 53
dollars a week. That's less than 400 dollars

00:12:31.050 --> 00:12:33.720
a week in 2011 dollars.

00:12:33.720 --> 00:12:39.240
Zulus in Durban, South Africa in 1960. Forty
percent of the women are obese. Women in their

00:12:39.240 --> 00:12:43.510
40s averaged 175 pounds. Today in the United
States, the average weight for adult women

00:12:43.510 --> 00:12:50.990
is around 165 pounds. Trinidad, early 60s,
Trinidad's having a malnutrition, a famine

00:12:50.990 --> 00:12:55.320
crisis. The US government sends a team of
nutritionists down to help out and they come

00:12:55.320 --> 00:13:01.630
back reporting that a third of women over
25 are obese. They report obesity as a "potentially

00:13:01.630 --> 00:13:04.980
serious medical problem in women." The per
capita data.

00:13:04.980 --> 00:13:10.610
The next year, an MIT nutritionist goes down
to Trinidad to figure out what's going on.

00:13:10.610 --> 00:13:15.529
She studies the diet of the obese women, compares
it to the diets of the lean women in Trinidad

00:13:15.529 --> 00:13:21.070
and concludes that the per capita daily diet
was less than 2000 calories a day, 21 percent

00:13:21.070 --> 00:13:26.710
fat. Fewer calories than were recommended
at the time by the Food and Agricultural Organization

00:13:26.710 --> 00:13:27.730
for a healthy diet.

00:13:27.730 --> 00:13:34.930
Bantu "pensioners" in South Africa in the
mid-60s. These are the poorest of a disenfranchised

00:13:34.930 --> 00:13:40.790
population. 30 percent of the women are severely
overweight and the mean weight of women over

00:13:40.790 --> 00:13:47.450
60 is 165 pounds. Raratonga in the South Pacific.
Forty percent of the women are obese, 25 percent

00:13:47.450 --> 00:13:51.110
are greatly obese, grossly obese. That's in
1971.

00:13:51.110 --> 00:13:56.700
And then, factory workers in Chile in 1974.
Thirty percent are obese. Nearly 50 percent

00:13:56.700 --> 00:14:02.490
of the women over 54 are obese. Ten percent
suffer undernourishment. OK, so here's that

00:14:02.490 --> 00:14:08.160
combination again of obesity and malnutrition
in the same population and most are engaged

00:14:08.160 --> 00:14:09.450
in heavy labor.

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:14.050
So, these are factory workers. They probably
don't belong to a gym. They probably don't

00:14:14.050 --> 00:14:19.050
have gyms in their factory in Chile in the
70s. They're not working out regularly. They're

00:14:19.050 --> 00:14:22.520
not training for marathons. They're probably
not doing triathlons.

00:14:22.520 --> 00:14:26.520
But they're engaged in heavy labor, heavy,
manual, physical labor. So we can assume on

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:31.460
a day-to-day basis they are more physically
active than we are. And yet, 30 percent are

00:14:31.460 --> 00:14:35.279
obese and nearly 50 percent--half of them--over
54.

00:14:35.279 --> 00:14:39.339
And here's the last study I'll show you. This
is Mexican Americans in Starr County, Texas

00:14:39.339 --> 00:14:45.860
in 1981. Fifty percent of the women in their
50s are obese, 40 percent of the men in their

00:14:45.860 --> 00:14:50.110
40s. And the living conditions, most inhabitants
are employed in agricultural labor and who

00:14:50.110 --> 00:14:58.370
work in the oil fields. So again, very physically
active population, but high levels of obesity.

00:14:58.370 --> 00:15:03.240
And there was one restaurant in Starr County,
Texas in 1981. Starr County is on the border

00:15:03.240 --> 00:15:08.500
of Mexico, about 200 miles due South of San
Antonio. And that was a Mexican restaurant.

00:15:08.500 --> 00:15:12.940
So again, this definition, there's no increased
prosperity for many of these populations.

00:15:12.940 --> 00:15:18.880
There's no prosperity at all. There's no toxic
environment as we would define it today. But

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:23.730
something's making them fat and we wanna know
what. Why were these populations fat? So if

00:15:23.730 --> 00:15:28.540
we can figure out why these populations were
fat, we can probably figure out why our populations

00:15:28.540 --> 00:15:29.940
are getting fat.

00:15:29.940 --> 00:15:35.410
So here's how this question was phrased in
1973. Ralph Richards was a university – he

00:15:35.410 --> 00:15:42.360
was a British-trained diabetes specialist
who went to Jamaica in the early 1960s, founded

00:15:42.360 --> 00:15:46.300
a diabetes clinic at the University of the
West Indies, and in the early 70s reported

00:15:46.300 --> 00:15:52.020
that a third of the women over 25 were obese
and that obesity reached what he called "monstrous

00:15:52.020 --> 00:15:56.380
proportions" in this age group. And he said,
"It's difficult to explain the high frequency

00:15:56.380 --> 00:16:01.660
of obesity seen in a relatively impecunious
society such as exists in the West Indies,

00:16:01.660 --> 00:16:04.600
when compared to the standard of living enjoyed
in the more developed countries."

00:16:04.600 --> 00:16:08.839
He's asking the same question I'm asking and
we all should be asking. If poor people are

00:16:08.839 --> 00:16:14.750
so fat, our theory says it’s the rich ones
who should be fat. "Malnutrition and sub nutrition

00:16:14.750 --> 00:16:18.610
are common disorders in the first two years
of life in these areas and account for almost

00:16:18.610 --> 00:16:23.110
25 percent of all admissions to pediatric
wards in Jamaica." So, by "sub nutrition",

00:16:23.110 --> 00:16:28.080
he means not enough food. "Sub nutrition continues
in early childhood to the early teens."

00:16:28.080 --> 00:16:32.970
So the children are stunted and show signs
of emaciation and then "obesity begins to

00:16:32.970 --> 00:16:38.780
manifest itself in the female population and
reaches enormous proportions from 30 onwards."

00:16:38.780 --> 00:16:44.190
So here's that question asked again. Exactly
the same observation, exactly the same question

00:16:44.190 --> 00:16:48.580
30 years later, this time by Benjamin Caballero
of Johns Hopkins.

00:16:48.580 --> 00:16:57.450
And now, within this paradigm of calories
in, calories out, of overeating. When, when

00:16:57.450 --> 00:17:02.180
Richards asked in 1973, he had an open mind.
He didn't know what the answer was. But now

00:17:02.180 --> 00:17:07.470
Benjamin Caballero thinks he knows the answer,
which is the answer we all think we know.

00:17:07.470 --> 00:17:11.959
And he says, a few years ago, this was in
the New England Journal of Medicine in 2005,

00:17:11.959 --> 00:17:16.350
an article called 'Obesity and Malnutrition:
A Nutrition Paradox'.

00:17:16.350 --> 00:17:20.200
He says, "A few years ago, I was visiting
a primary care clinic in the slums of São

00:17:20.200 --> 00:17:22.380
Paulo, Brazil. The waiting room was full of
mothers with thin, stunted young children,

00:17:22.380 --> 00:17:25.760
exhibiting the typical signs of chronic under
nutrition. Their appearance, sadly, would

00:17:25.760 --> 00:17:32.570
surprise few who visit poor urban areas in
the developing world. What might come as a

00:17:32.570 --> 00:17:36.600
surprise is that many of the mothers holding
those under-nourished infants were themselves

00:17:36.600 --> 00:17:37.600
overweight."

00:17:37.600 --> 00:17:41.650
And then he says, "The coexistence of underweight
and overweight poses a challenge to public

00:17:41.650 --> 00:17:47.300
health programs, since the aims of programs
to reduce under nutrition" --which is get

00:17:47.300 --> 00:17:52.940
people to eat more, make more food available—"are
obviously in conflict with those for obesity

00:17:52.940 --> 00:17:57.300
prevention" --which is make less food available.
So we have a problem.

00:17:57.300 --> 00:18:04.440
And I put this "poses a challenge to public
health programs" in italics because the coexistence

00:18:04.440 --> 00:18:08.991
of underweight and overweight poses a challenge
to your paradigm, your belief system. If you

00:18:08.991 --> 00:18:13.230
believe that the mothers got fat because they
took in more calories than they expended,

00:18:13.230 --> 00:18:19.200
they took in superfluous calories that they
didn't need, and the children aren't getting

00:18:19.200 --> 00:18:24.360
enough food, then you believe that the mothers
are willing to starve their children to death

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:28.420
so that they can sneak outside and eat a Snickers
bar, in effect.

00:18:28.420 --> 00:18:32.980
And I don't know how many, this is a young
audience, how many mothers are there in this

00:18:32.980 --> 00:18:35.780
audience? OK. How many of you would do that?

00:18:35.780 --> 00:18:36.990
[laughter]

00:18:36.990 --> 00:18:42.460
Let your children starve so you can get fat,
as opposed to, perhaps, the other way around,

00:18:42.460 --> 00:18:47.980
right? So you've got two paradigms colliding.
We've got our paradigm maternal behavior that

00:18:47.980 --> 00:18:54.429
says population, species don't survive unless
the mothers make sacrifices for their children.

00:18:54.429 --> 00:19:00.230
And we have the paradigm of obesity that says
these mothers are just happily guzzling excess

00:19:00.230 --> 00:19:03.050
calories while they're watching their kids
starve to death.

00:19:03.050 --> 00:19:09.200
And this is an anomalous observation. I used
to, started my career writing about high-energy

00:19:09.200 --> 00:19:13.460
physics, and high-energy physics, they just
built the Large Hadron Collidor at CERN that

00:19:13.460 --> 00:19:18.580
costs I forget how many billions of dollars,
all designed to just create an observation

00:19:18.580 --> 00:19:22.250
that their theory can't explain so they can
proceed onward.

00:19:22.250 --> 00:19:27.710
Here, we've had this observation going back
probably to 1928 at least, and nobody cares.

00:19:27.710 --> 00:19:31.880
And my point is you have to throw out one
of the two paradigms. And I'm gonna throw

00:19:31.880 --> 00:19:36.230
out the obesity paradigm 'cause my mother--
may she rest in peace-- would have killed

00:19:36.230 --> 00:19:41.510
me if I threw out the maternal behavior paradigm.

00:19:41.510 --> 00:19:44.870
Let's look at some other inconvenient observations,
Okay?

00:19:44.870 --> 00:19:49.840
"Eating less doesn't work." Our hypothesis
is that if we eat more, if we take in more

00:19:49.840 --> 00:19:55.090
calories than we expend, we will gain weight.
So the idea is if we take in less calories

00:19:55.090 --> 00:19:59.780
than you expend, you'll lose weight. All you
have to do is create what's called "negative

00:19:59.780 --> 00:20:06.520
energy balance." So you go on a semi-restricted
calorie diet and there are a lot of meta-analysis

00:20:06.520 --> 00:20:11.559
over the years, systematic reviews, showing
how poorly these work.

00:20:11.559 --> 00:20:15.500
The Cochrane Collaboration a few years ago
when they looked at this. The Cochrane Collaboration

00:20:15.500 --> 00:20:22.750
is a collaboration created just to do unbiased
reviews of the data. Their assumption being

00:20:22.750 --> 00:20:27.309
every other review of the data is biased.
So we have to create the methodology that

00:20:27.309 --> 00:20:31.471
doesn't allow bias to enter into it. And with
this, they put it back in--I think it was

00:20:31.471 --> 00:20:37.679
2002, I can't see my notes, unfortunately,
because we're not in notes mode, here--the

00:20:37.679 --> 00:20:43.900
weight loss achieved, that was 2002. It's
so small as to be clinically insignificant.

00:20:43.900 --> 00:20:48.220
And what you see in the literature is fascinating
'cause people, they try to deal with this

00:20:48.220 --> 00:20:52.179
when they write about obesity; the fact that
eating less doesn’t work. But they believe

00:20:52.179 --> 00:20:54.710
that a calorie-restricted diet is crucial.

00:20:54.710 --> 00:21:02.280
So you'll see these chapters in obesity textbooks,
like the 'Task Force of Obesity', Task Force

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:09.690
textbook, where the researchers will write
that restricting calories is the fundamental

00:21:09.690 --> 00:21:17.590
approach, the -- I forget the word they use
because I don't have my notes-- to curing

00:21:17.590 --> 00:21:21.870
obesity, yet it rarely, if ever, works.

00:21:21.870 --> 00:21:26.920
Exercising more also doesn't work. One of
the problems here, I could also show you meta-analyses

00:21:26.920 --> 00:21:33.480
that talk about how clinically insignificant
this effect is. But there's, the best evidence

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:38.610
I found so far for this is the American Heart
Association and the American College of Sports

00:21:38.610 --> 00:21:44.510
Medicine in 2007, put out their physical activity
guidelines. And the physical activity guidelines--these

00:21:44.510 --> 00:21:50.010
are people, two organizations, that want us
to engage in healthy lifestyles, that believe

00:21:50.010 --> 00:21:52.340
that physical activity should make a difference.

00:21:52.340 --> 00:21:57.640
And you would expect them to spin the data
in favor of physical activity for exercise,

00:21:57.640 --> 00:22:02.350
for weight loss--and the way they put it is
this. They said, "It is reasonable to assume

00:22:02.350 --> 00:22:07.330
that persons with relatively high daily energy
expenditures would be less likely to gain

00:22:07.330 --> 00:22:11.170
weight over time, compared to those who have
low energy expenditures."

00:22:11.170 --> 00:22:15.210
That's logically equivalent to saying, "It's
reasonable to assume that if you're a couch

00:22:15.210 --> 00:22:20.170
potato and you increase your energy expenditure,
you will be less likely to gain weight than

00:22:20.170 --> 00:22:22.970
if you remain a couch potato."

00:22:22.970 --> 00:22:27.679
And then they say, "So far, data to support
this hypothesis are not particularly compelling."

00:22:27.679 --> 00:22:33.500
And the point of this is this hypothesis is
in the neighborhood of 100 to 150 years old.

00:22:33.500 --> 00:22:38.980
There, you could find obesity texts in the
1860s in which somebody like William Banting

00:22:38.980 --> 00:22:44.040
talks about his doctor telling him to go for
a row every morning to burn off calories.

00:22:44.040 --> 00:22:48.710
He also talks about how it didn't help. You
could find in, by the 1890s, when the laws

00:22:48.710 --> 00:22:54.100
of thermodynamics [clears throat] had been
shown to hold with animate objects as well

00:22:54.100 --> 00:22:58.370
as inanimate objects, with living beings as
well as inanimate objects, researchers said,

00:22:58.370 --> 00:23:02.750
"Hey, maybe if we just get people to expend
more energy, they'll gain weight. I mean they'll

00:23:02.750 --> 00:23:08.120
lose weight and over the course of a hundred
years, 150 years, this is the best we could

00:23:08.120 --> 00:23:12.290
say about it. "The data to support this hypothesis
are not particularly compelling."

00:23:12.290 --> 00:23:17.730
And that's a bad sign. When I was writing
about high-energy physics, it was an unwritten

00:23:17.730 --> 00:23:22.850
rule of high-energy physics by Pief Panofsky,
who's a founder of the Stanford Linear Accelerator

00:23:22.850 --> 00:23:28.060
Center here. And Pief said, "If you throw
money at an effect and it doesn't get bigger,

00:23:28.060 --> 00:23:30.230
it means it's not really there." Okay?

00:23:30.230 --> 00:23:35.270
And the corollary here is if you've been studying
an effect, for a century and the best you

00:23:35.270 --> 00:23:37.190
could say about it is "the data to support
this hypothesis are not particularly compelling",

00:23:37.190 --> 00:23:44.720
there's a very good chance that your hypothesis
is wrong; that increasing energy expenditure

00:23:44.720 --> 00:23:49.340
and physical activity will have no effect
on how much you weigh, or how much weight

00:23:49.340 --> 00:23:50.340
you've gained.

00:23:50.340 --> 00:23:56.780
And one way to think about this and to this
I owe a British blogger. Imagine that I'm

00:23:56.780 --> 00:24:03.190
having, I'm hosting a dinner party tonight
and I've got the ten last finalists from Top

00:24:03.190 --> 00:24:09.880
Chef cooking. And they're making this amazing
feast and I send you all invitations and I

00:24:09.880 --> 00:24:14.320
say, "I've got this feast. It's gonna be a
ton of the best tasting food you've ever eaten

00:24:14.320 --> 00:24:22.080
in your life. Come hungry." What would you
do to make sure you came hungry? And here

00:24:22.080 --> 00:24:25.140
I'll take questions. Anyone wanna answer?
What would you do during the day?

00:24:25.140 --> 00:24:29.921
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #1: Skip snacks.

00:24:29.921 --> 00:24:30.921
&gt;&gt;Gary Taubes: Skip snacks, eat less.

00:24:30.921 --> 00:24:32.540
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #1: I would take
a long walk.

00:24:32.540 --> 00:24:36.290
&gt;&gt;Gary Taubes: And take a long walk. Exercise
more. You'd work out.

00:24:36.290 --> 00:24:40.580
So the exact same things that we prescribe
overweight people to lose weight are the two

00:24:40.580 --> 00:24:46.590
things that you're going to do if you wanna
guarantee that you get hungry and eat more.

00:24:46.590 --> 00:24:47.900
And we're gonna explain that in a while.

00:24:47.900 --> 00:24:53.049
But you can see already that there's something
wrong here. Here's another problem with our

00:24:53.049 --> 00:24:58.580
energy balance idea. Practicing energy balance
is impossible. This is a new phrase you hear.

00:24:58.580 --> 00:25:04.410
The past two or three years, the idea there
are now industry programs developed in collaboration

00:25:04.410 --> 00:25:08.810
with the government to help you practice energy
balance, to make sure you match calories in

00:25:08.810 --> 00:25:10.549
to calories out so you don't gain weight.

00:25:10.549 --> 00:25:14.690
And the industry loves the idea. The food
industry loves the idea of obesity being all

00:25:14.690 --> 00:25:19.570
about calories, because you can't demonize
anything. It's all about just it's your fault

00:25:19.570 --> 00:25:23.050
if you're overweight. You just have to eat
less and exercise more and if you wanna build

00:25:23.050 --> 00:25:26.910
a gym in your neighborhood, or a track or
a park, go to Coke or Pepsi and ask them for

00:25:26.910 --> 00:25:30.610
money. They'll give it to you 'cause they
would like you to exercise more so that way,

00:25:30.610 --> 00:25:33.110
they can't be blamed for your obesity epidemic.

00:25:33.110 --> 00:25:37.740
So, let's see what it takes actually to practice
energy balance. A typical American's food

00:25:37.740 --> 00:25:43.150
intake is about 2700 calories a day. Okay?
That's men and women. So that's a million

00:25:43.150 --> 00:25:48.990
calories a year. Ten million calories in a
decade, Okay? It's about ten to twelve tons

00:25:48.990 --> 00:25:51.250
of food per decade.

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:57.190
Now, all you'd have to do is ask the question.
Let's say, right now, I'm a 25 year old and

00:25:57.190 --> 00:26:04.860
I'm lean and I wanna ask the question, "How
well do I have to maintain energy balance?

00:26:04.860 --> 00:26:09.940
How well do I have to practice energy balance
so that I don't gain 20 pounds in a decade,

00:26:09.940 --> 00:26:17.330
40 pounds in 20 years, so by the time I'm
in my mid-40s I'm obese?" What is that entail,

00:26:17.330 --> 00:26:19.260
because that's what the government is trying
to get us to do.

00:26:19.260 --> 00:26:24.780
And the answer is you have to maintain your
energy balance to 20 calories per day. If

00:26:24.780 --> 00:26:30.300
over 20 -- this is actually a trick answer,
because if 20 calories per day goes into your

00:26:30.300 --> 00:26:36.550
fat tissue that you don't burn, you will gain
40 pounds in 20 years. Here's the calculation.

00:26:36.550 --> 00:26:38.240
It's pretty simple. Very simple.

00:26:38.240 --> 00:26:45.760
Even I could do this and I don't work at Google.
Twenty calories times 365 days a year times

00:26:45.760 --> 00:26:50.110
ten years, divided by 35 hundred, which is
the number of calories, roughly, in a pound

00:26:50.110 --> 00:26:55.500
of fat. And you end up with 21 pounds in a
decade. Okay? So if you go over that, if you

00:26:55.500 --> 00:27:00.230
can match your energy in to your energy out,
to 20 calories a day and not exceed that on

00:27:00.230 --> 00:27:04.290
average, you'll only gain 40 pounds. If you
only want to gain 20 pounds, it's ten calories.

00:27:04.290 --> 00:27:08.250
If you don't want to gain any weight, of course,
the idea is you have to do it perfectly.

00:27:08.250 --> 00:27:15.419
Twenty calories a day is .8 percent accuracy.
Nobody can do that. Nobody, even I will bet

00:27:15.419 --> 00:27:23.110
my life's income--it's not that big--that
the world champion calorie counter in the

00:27:23.110 --> 00:27:27.190
world, Guinness -- if there is such an entry
in Guinness, cannot gauge within 20 calories

00:27:27.190 --> 00:27:30.799
how much food they were eating per day and
then you have no idea how much you're expending.

00:27:30.799 --> 00:27:37.210
You're just guessing, even when you go in
to do research sessions. They just do calculations.

00:27:37.210 --> 00:27:43.390
So the point here is I got this calculation
from a 1937 Nutrition and Metabolism textbook,

00:27:43.390 --> 00:27:47.960
written by a fellow named Eugene Dubois, who's
a leading expert on metabolism in the United

00:27:47.960 --> 00:27:53.660
States, pre-World War II. [pause] And Dubois
uses calculations. He said what's interesting

00:27:53.660 --> 00:27:59.539
about it is since nobody can do that, how
do we maintain our weight? The question isn't

00:27:59.539 --> 00:28:03.870
why are some of us fat? The question should
be why aren't all of us fat? Okay?

00:28:03.870 --> 00:28:08.990
Because if you overshoot by even 20 calories
a day on average, you're gonna end up getting

00:28:08.990 --> 00:28:13.950
obese. And you could say, "Okay. Maybe one
way to do it is I just watch my weight. I

00:28:13.950 --> 00:28:18.360
look in the mirror. I see I'm getting fatter.
My belt's getting snug, or my pants, or my

00:28:18.360 --> 00:28:22.650
skirt doesn't fit. So therefore, I'm gonna
eat less for a while until I get my weight

00:28:22.650 --> 00:28:23.650
back."

00:28:23.650 --> 00:28:26.370
So you oscillate around perfect energy balance,
but then you have to ask the question, how

00:28:26.370 --> 00:28:30.760
do animals do it? Because they don't. They're
not looking in the mirror. They don't have

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:34.820
clothes they're putting on. So how do they
maintain their weight and virtually all animals

00:28:34.820 --> 00:28:39.110
do? They don't get chronically obese. So the
idea that Dubois says it's obviously something

00:28:39.110 --> 00:28:43.510
else is going on here, other than consciously
matching calories in to calories out, which

00:28:43.510 --> 00:28:44.910
none of us can do.

00:28:44.910 --> 00:28:51.070
So let's look at some other inconvenient observations.

00:28:51.070 --> 00:28:54.990
Genetics is one of them. I gotta apologize
now. If you go to an obesity textbook today,

00:28:54.990 --> 00:29:00.169
you will not see photos of naked human beings.
But if you go to an obesity textbook pre-

00:29:00.169 --> 00:29:04.820
World War II, you would. Because those researchers,
those clinicians, thought you could learn

00:29:04.820 --> 00:29:09.480
a lot about watching how people fatten, as
well as just whether they do or not.

00:29:09.480 --> 00:29:14.090
And one of the things I'm doing now is just
channeling these pre-World War II researchers.

00:29:14.090 --> 00:29:20.470
And in fact, all I'm saying in my books is
I'm taking the theory that German and Austrian

00:29:20.470 --> 00:29:25.000
researchers developed pre-World War II, back
when the Germans and Austrians did the best

00:29:25.000 --> 00:29:29.850
medical research in the world and there was
virtually no meaningful medical research being

00:29:29.850 --> 00:29:31.400
done in the United States.

00:29:31.400 --> 00:29:36.960
And I'm taking that theory and I'm updating
it. Okay? Because they didn't survive the

00:29:36.960 --> 00:29:42.270
war. That community didn't survive the war.
So, for starters, here's genetics. And there's

00:29:42.270 --> 00:29:50.030
a pair -- and this comes from a 1940 textbook.
Here's a pair of lean identical twins. Here's

00:29:50.030 --> 00:29:55.190
a pair of obese identical twins. Our overeating
hypothesis might explain why these women are

00:29:55.190 --> 00:30:00.350
fatter than these women. These took in too
many calories and these practiced perfect

00:30:00.350 --> 00:30:01.570
energy balance.

00:30:01.570 --> 00:30:05.540
But what about this combination? Why do they
have the same body type? And why do they have

00:30:05.540 --> 00:30:09.450
the same body type? It's been known since
the 1930s that obesity has a strong genetic

00:30:09.450 --> 00:30:14.070
component. Identical twins – it's not that
their faces look alike. Their body types are

00:30:14.070 --> 00:30:16.160
the same, too. So what's going on here?

00:30:16.160 --> 00:30:21.530
What do these genes determine? Do they determine
exactly how much these women, how many forkfuls

00:30:21.530 --> 00:30:27.000
of food these women overate over 20, 30, 40
years? And exactly how long they sat on a

00:30:27.000 --> 00:30:29.160
couch versus going for a walk?

00:30:29.160 --> 00:30:34.650
Or, did they determine something else about
how much and where they accumulated fat 'cause

00:30:34.650 --> 00:30:37.610
they have the identical body?

00:30:37.610 --> 00:30:41.330
Here's a different variation of an animal
husbandry and it's even easier to see here

00:30:41.330 --> 00:30:46.580
what I'm talking about. Farmers, livestock
breeders, have been breeding more or less

00:30:46.580 --> 00:30:54.539
fatty cows, pigs, sheep, for centuries, probably.
And here's a particularly fat breed of beef

00:30:54.539 --> 00:30:59.380
cattle. This is an Aberdeen Angus. Here's
the meat. I should say it's stocky, but you

00:30:59.380 --> 00:31:07.890
can see all the subcutaneous fat, the intramuscular
fat, here. And here's a lean species, a lean

00:31:07.890 --> 00:31:12.580
breed of cattle, the Jersey Cow. And you can
see the ribs showing, you can see the swollen

00:31:12.580 --> 00:31:15.550
udder. It's definitely a dairy cow.

00:31:15.550 --> 00:31:18.419
And you can ask yourself simply, there are
different breeds. Obviously, different genes

00:31:18.419 --> 00:31:22.160
are determining how much they get fat. What
exactly is going on here? What are these genes

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:27.870
determining? Do they determine how much these
animals eat and exercise? Do they determine

00:31:27.870 --> 00:31:35.809
how many calories per graze, or per bite of
grass, this cow takes? The Aberdeen Angus

00:31:35.809 --> 00:31:41.090
grazes for 12 hours. The Jersey only grazes
for ten a day. Does the Jersey want to go

00:31:41.090 --> 00:31:47.880
to work out? So, on the Far Side cartoon when
it gets dark at night, the Jersey goes for

00:31:47.880 --> 00:31:53.130
a jog. The Aberdeen Angus goes in and watches
television. And it's obviously absurd, Okay?

00:31:53.130 --> 00:31:56.990
Whatever determines how much these animals
get fat, we can be confident that how much

00:31:56.990 --> 00:32:02.040
they eat and exercise has nothing to do with
it. More likely, and again, this is a beef

00:32:02.040 --> 00:32:07.760
cow. So what you want is it's an effectively,
brutally speaking and I apologize for the

00:32:07.760 --> 00:32:16.470
vegetarians here, to the vegetarians here.
It's a machine that takes in fuel here and

00:32:16.470 --> 00:32:19.929
deposits it here and you want it all to go
here.

00:32:19.929 --> 00:32:24.640
So you could assume that it just partitions
the calories it eats into fat and protein.

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:29.970
And the Jersey Cow, you want to create milk.
So you take in the fuel and it's all gonna

00:32:29.970 --> 00:32:34.730
go to the udders to produce milk. And you
don't want it wasting energy, in effect, bulking

00:32:34.730 --> 00:32:39.640
up. So maybe what these genes determine is
not how many calories we take in, but how

00:32:39.640 --> 00:32:43.590
we partition the fuel we take in.

00:32:43.590 --> 00:32:48.870
That's a technical term. Sexual variations.
Men and women fatten differently, Okay? Men

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:52.881
fatten above the waist. Women fatten below
the waist. Both these people would have had

00:32:52.881 --> 00:32:57.809
to overeat, take in more calories than they
expend to get fat. This has doubled his risk

00:32:57.809 --> 00:33:01.919
of heart disease. This has not doubled her
risk. If the weight's below the waist, it

00:33:01.919 --> 00:33:05.410
doesn't double your risk. What do the calories
have to do with it?

00:33:05.410 --> 00:33:09.720
Okay? And what do the calories have to do
with where they get fat, because obviously,

00:33:09.720 --> 00:33:14.299
that's a huge component of it. And another
way to look at it is puberty. Men and women,

00:33:14.299 --> 00:33:20.669
when they go through puberty, boys, they begin
puberty with roughly the same amount of body

00:33:20.669 --> 00:33:25.510
fat. When boys go through puberty, they lose
fat and gain muscle. When girls go through

00:33:25.510 --> 00:33:29.370
puberty, they gain fat and breasts and hips
and buttocks.

00:33:29.370 --> 00:33:34.080
And by the time they're out of puberty, the
girls have about 50 percent more fat on their

00:33:34.080 --> 00:33:39.080
bodies than the men. Both boys and girls got
bigger. So they both overate. They both took

00:33:39.080 --> 00:33:43.890
in more calories than they expend, but the
boys lost fat and gained muscle. The girls

00:33:43.890 --> 00:33:44.890
gained fat in specific places.

00:33:44.890 --> 00:33:49.560
So you just ask the question, what do the
calories have to do with it? What did the

00:33:49.560 --> 00:33:55.400
fact of their overeating have to do with whether
or not they gained muscle or fat? And this

00:33:55.400 --> 00:34:03.260
is obviously controlled by sex and growth
hormones and that's an issue we'll get to.

00:34:03.260 --> 00:34:08.899
Now, lipidystrophies. This is again, from
the same 1940 textbook, which took it from

00:34:08.899 --> 00:34:13.110
a 1933 German text book. This is a lipidystrophy
called a progressive lipidystrophy. In the

00:34:13.110 --> 00:34:19.079
1950s, there were about 200 of these on record.
Most of them were in women. It's called progressive

00:34:19.079 --> 00:34:24.200
'cause these cases, they begin losing all
subcutaneous fat in the face, in their forehead,

00:34:24.200 --> 00:34:26.469
and it moves downward with time.

00:34:26.469 --> 00:34:31.190
One British physician reported that his patient
lost fat at about one inch a year. That's

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:35.469
why it's progressive. And then it usually
stops above the hips. And then they often

00:34:35.469 --> 00:34:40.659
get this lower body, localized obesity below
the waist. So the way these Europeans asked

00:34:40.659 --> 00:34:46.599
it, they said, "Are we gonna blame the top
half on under eating and bottom half on overeating?"

00:34:46.599 --> 00:34:47.599
[laughter]

00:34:47.599 --> 00:34:52.010
Right? And this is again, obviously absurd.
It's like a Gedanken Experiment. But if this

00:34:52.010 --> 00:34:56.859
woman had ten pounds more fat on her upper
body, maybe even five pounds, just to smooth

00:34:56.859 --> 00:35:02.569
out her curves, her BMI was about 32 already
just cause of her lower body obesity. And

00:35:02.569 --> 00:35:07.059
she went into the doctor then. The doctor
wouldn't recognize the lipidystrophy. And

00:35:07.059 --> 00:35:10.430
he would just say, "Look, eat less and exercise
more."

00:35:10.430 --> 00:35:17.160
And the point that the Europeans are making
is if you can't explain the localized conditions

00:35:17.160 --> 00:35:21.420
by under eating and overeating, why would
you even think to explain the generalized

00:35:21.420 --> 00:35:25.680
obesity by overeating? Or, in those cases,
often these textbooks, pre-World War II were

00:35:25.680 --> 00:35:30.829
titled 'Obesity and Leanness' because they
were looking at cases that today we would

00:35:30.829 --> 00:35:35.859
call anorexia and assuming that that also
wasn't an under eating problem. It was some

00:35:35.859 --> 00:35:38.839
problem of how the fat tissue was regulated.

00:35:38.839 --> 00:35:42.769
So why do we believe this? And let's look
at a little physics here, Okay? And this is

00:35:42.769 --> 00:35:46.640
the reason.

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:50.380
[pause]

00:35:50.380 --> 00:35:54.549
We believe it 'cause of the first law of thermodynamics.
Every time somebody like me makes this point

00:35:54.549 --> 00:35:59.779
for the past 50, 60 years, you get accused
of not believing that thermodynamics holds

00:35:59.779 --> 00:36:00.789
for human beings.

00:36:00.789 --> 00:36:06.019
I had one of the high points of my life. I
was on the Larry King Show after 'Good Calories,

00:36:06.019 --> 00:36:10.950
Bad Calories' came out. And they had Jillian
Michaels, the trainer from 'The Biggest Loser',

00:36:10.950 --> 00:36:15.479
come on. And she gave me a lecture on the
laws of thermodynamics on national television.

00:36:15.479 --> 00:36:17.799
And I have a physics degree from Harvard.

00:36:17.799 --> 00:36:18.799
[laughter]

00:36:18.799 --> 00:36:23.809
I mean, I was a, I was a lousy student, but
it was definitely, I literally, I'm sitting

00:36:23.809 --> 00:36:28.329
next to. I just, I didn't respond. If you
watch the show, it's on, you can Google it.

00:36:28.329 --> 00:36:31.489
I didn't know what to say. I mean, how do
I respond to this?

00:36:31.489 --> 00:36:36.760
So lemme give you a little, thermodynamics
is pretty simple. The first law of thermodynamics

00:36:36.760 --> 00:36:40.469
-- it's the law of energy conservation. It
says a change in energy in a system--this

00:36:40.469 --> 00:36:43.819
is the simplest possible way to put it-- is
equal to the energy in minus energy out. All

00:36:43.819 --> 00:36:48.099
it's saying is you can't create energy from
thin air.

00:36:48.099 --> 00:36:52.950
So, if a system gets bigger, delta E goes
up. And it's gotta take in more energy than

00:36:52.950 --> 00:36:56.880
it expends. And if a system gets smaller,
it's got to expend more energy than it takes

00:36:56.880 --> 00:37:02.200
in. For our sake, we'll make delta E the fat
mass E in is energy consumed, E out energy

00:37:02.200 --> 00:37:06.729
expended. So change in fat mass equals energy
consumed minus energy expended.

00:37:06.729 --> 00:37:12.979
And the problem, the fundamental problem,
and it's almost unbelievable to me, is that

00:37:12.979 --> 00:37:19.200
there's no arrow of causality here. And by
that I mean it doesn't say in any way if energy,

00:37:19.200 --> 00:37:23.769
energy consumed greater than energy expended
causes change of fat mass. It just says this

00:37:23.769 --> 00:37:24.900
is the way the universe is.

00:37:24.900 --> 00:37:29.965
If a system gets bigger, it takes in more
energy than it expends. And if a system gets

00:37:29.965 --> 00:37:34.680
smaller, it takes in less. It says nothing
about what causes it. And to understand that,

00:37:34.680 --> 00:37:39.029
a metaphor I could use. Like, let's assume
I was asking the question why is this room

00:37:39.029 --> 00:37:41.749
crowded right now? Okay?

00:37:41.749 --> 00:37:45.489
And it's as similar when we're talking about
fat mass. We wanna know, why is there so much

00:37:45.489 --> 00:37:48.920
energy accumulated in the fat mass? And I
wanna ask the question, why is there so much

00:37:48.920 --> 00:37:53.819
energy accumulated in this room in the form
of people? So you ask me, "Gary, why is it

00:37:53.819 --> 00:37:58.319
crowded?" And I say, "Well, because more people
entered than left."

00:37:58.319 --> 00:37:59.319
[pause]

00:37:59.319 --> 00:38:03.599
Right? Have I told you anything meaningful
at all about why this?

00:38:03.599 --> 00:38:04.599
[laughter]

00:38:04.599 --> 00:38:07.910
I mean, of course more people entered than
left. But why is it crowded? And then I say,

00:38:07.910 --> 00:38:13.549
"Well, look. If more people enter than leave,
it's gotta get crowded, right?" And I still

00:38:13.549 --> 00:38:14.839
haven't told you anything meaningful.

00:38:14.839 --> 00:38:22.569
This is what magicians would call--I forget
the word--vacuous? It's the equivalent as

00:38:22.569 --> 00:38:26.029
saying, why did you get fat? Because you took
in more energy than you expended. Well, of

00:38:26.029 --> 00:38:31.329
course I took in more energy than I expended.
I got fat. But why did I get fat? And then

00:38:31.329 --> 00:38:35.680
you just turn around and say, "Well, if you
take in more energy than you expend," there's

00:38:35.680 --> 00:38:39.819
no arrow of causality. There's nothing meaningful
here.

00:38:39.819 --> 00:38:45.960
This is a mistake that was made occasionally
prior to the Second World War. It became ubiquitous

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:50.299
after the Second World War. Whenever we tell
someone, "You got fat 'cause you overate,"

00:38:50.299 --> 00:38:55.660
you are misinterpreting the laws of thermodynamics
on an eighth grade mathematics level.

00:38:55.660 --> 00:39:00.359
And the more I talk about it, the more it's
almost unbelievable that this ever happened.

00:39:00.359 --> 00:39:04.489
And yet, it did. And so there's another way
you could play with this thermodynamics. And

00:39:04.489 --> 00:39:09.369
for this I owe University of Washington grad
student named Sonya Trejo, who said, "What

00:39:09.369 --> 00:39:11.950
happens if you start transposing elements?"

00:39:11.950 --> 00:39:16.809
So how about this. Instead of, we had delta
E over here and E out over here. How about

00:39:16.809 --> 00:39:20.940
if we say energy out is equal to energy in
minus delta E? And so now, the energy expended

00:39:20.940 --> 00:39:24.569
is equal to energy consumed minus change in
fat mass, Okay?

00:39:24.569 --> 00:39:29.960
So if fat mass gets bigger -- for we don't
know why, we're working on that -- and the

00:39:29.960 --> 00:39:35.880
person doesn't eat anymore, then energy expenditure
has to go down. Okay? So you look at it this

00:39:35.880 --> 00:39:42.509
way and an increase in fat mass causes sedentary
behavior. If fat mass gets smaller, energy

00:39:42.509 --> 00:39:44.670
expended has to go up.

00:39:44.670 --> 00:39:48.900
So if somebody's losing weight, they have
to get more physically active. Or how about

00:39:48.900 --> 00:39:53.309
this one? We just do a little more transposing
and we end up with energy in equals delta

00:39:53.309 --> 00:39:58.200
E plus energy out. So the energy we eat is
equal to change in fat mass plus energy expended.

00:39:58.200 --> 00:40:03.569
Let's assume change in fat mass is fixed by
biology. And if you read the New York Times

00:40:03.569 --> 00:40:08.660
today there was an article about that. And
energy expenditure goes up 'cause I just told

00:40:08.660 --> 00:40:13.380
you to work out. What's gonna happen to energy
consumed? It has to go up. You're gonna get

00:40:13.380 --> 00:40:15.230
hungry. You will work up an appetite.

00:40:15.230 --> 00:40:19.950
This used to be something that everyone believed
in the 1960s and beyond. There used to be

00:40:19.950 --> 00:40:24.700
this term, "working up an appetite." So it
used to be, if you worked out, you worked

00:40:24.700 --> 00:40:28.230
up an appetite. Now if you work out, you're
supposed to lose weight and energy consumed

00:40:28.230 --> 00:40:32.880
is supposed to stay fixed. But there's no
guarantee this'll happen.

00:40:32.880 --> 00:40:39.089
So here's the alternative hypothesis. This
is the way that the pre-World War II Europeans

00:40:39.089 --> 00:40:44.380
thought about it. They said, started from
first principles, obesity is a disorder of

00:40:44.380 --> 00:40:46.130
excess fat accumulation.

00:40:46.130 --> 00:40:52.469
So today, you read obesity is a positive energy
balance, or obesity is an energy balance problem

00:40:52.469 --> 00:40:56.469
and those are assumptions. They just started
at the beginning. Having too much fat is a

00:40:56.469 --> 00:41:00.739
disorder of having too much fat. So it's not
energy balance. It's not overeating. It's

00:41:00.739 --> 00:41:04.789
not sedentary behavior. And if you ask it
this way, the next question you're likely

00:41:04.789 --> 00:41:09.180
to ask, which we'll get to, is what regulates
fat accumulation? Because what we know is

00:41:09.180 --> 00:41:10.180
there's too much fat.

00:41:10.180 --> 00:41:14.539
Like, if I was standing in here with Yao Ming,
whose seven feet six inches tall, and we wanted

00:41:14.539 --> 00:41:18.719
to know why he grew to be seven foot six,
we wouldn't care that he was in positive energy

00:41:18.719 --> 00:41:22.680
balance. We would want to know what regulates
growth, right. So we wanna know what regulates

00:41:22.680 --> 00:41:27.359
growth. So, by this hypothesis, overeating
and inactivity are compensatory effects. They're

00:41:27.359 --> 00:41:28.739
not causes.

00:41:28.739 --> 00:41:33.029
And the way it was put to me by several different
individuals doing animal research, so we don't

00:41:33.029 --> 00:41:38.660
get fat because we overeat. We overeat because
our fat tissue is accumulating excess fat.

00:41:38.660 --> 00:41:42.390
Overeating is a given. If you're getting fatter,
you have to take in more calories than you

00:41:42.390 --> 00:41:49.690
consume. But we're saying the positive energy
balance is in effect.

00:41:49.690 --> 00:41:53.970
Here's a way to see it. This comes from the,
again, straight out of the pre World War II

00:41:53.970 --> 00:42:01.779
text. Although the child is mine, I use these
photos 'cause he's so cute. He was. Here he

00:42:01.779 --> 00:42:09.200
was one year old, 20 pounds. Okay? 2006. Here
he is 2009, 45 pounds. He's gained 25 pounds

00:42:09.200 --> 00:42:13.130
in three years, right? He's been in positive
energy balance. He has overeaten.

00:42:13.130 --> 00:42:14.130
[laughter]

00:42:14.130 --> 00:42:18.789
He's taken in more calories than expended.
But he did not take in, he did not grow because

00:42:18.789 --> 00:42:25.910
he overate. He overate because he was growing.
He grew cause he was secreting growth hormone.

00:42:25.910 --> 00:42:31.309
And the growth hormone sparked his tissues
to grow muscle, organs, fat, bone. And he

00:42:31.309 --> 00:42:36.890
had to take in more calories than he expended
to fuel that growth. And if he wasn't growing

00:42:36.890 --> 00:42:41.450
fast enough, we might have even given him
more growth hormone to speed his growth, at

00:42:41.450 --> 00:42:44.680
which point that would have created even more
positive energy balance.

00:42:44.680 --> 00:42:50.510
Here's a gruesome analogy: cancer. Here's
a tumor. You can barely see it. Then it's

00:42:50.510 --> 00:42:55.309
growing at Day 10. It's growing at Day 20.
It's bigger and bigger. This tumor is in positive

00:42:55.309 --> 00:43:01.700
energy balance; nobody cares. We care if we
want to starve it to death, but that's a given.

00:43:01.700 --> 00:43:06.109
Like, just if we don't want this room to get
crowded, we'll shut the doors before anyone

00:43:06.109 --> 00:43:11.880
comes in. But what we care about is what genes,
what hormones are disruptive that drive the

00:43:11.880 --> 00:43:15.619
growth because the positive energy balance
is in effect.

00:43:15.619 --> 00:43:21.549
And in every other example in nature, positive
energy balance is always an effect of growth,

00:43:21.549 --> 00:43:23.230
not the other way around.

00:43:23.230 --> 00:43:27.349
So, this was a German-Austrian hypothesis
prior to World War II. It was known as the

00:43:27.349 --> 00:43:33.719
lipophilia hypothesis. I'll explain that in
a second. The primary proponents where Gustav

00:43:33.719 --> 00:43:39.730
von Bergmann, who was a German specialist
in internal medicine. Today the highest award

00:43:39.730 --> 00:43:44.200
in the German Association of Internal Medicine
is the Gustav von Bergmann Award.

00:43:44.200 --> 00:43:49.950
And then Julius Bauer, who was a geneticist
and endocrinologist at the University of Vienna,

00:43:49.950 --> 00:43:54.959
Bauer was very famous in Austria. If you have
any molecular biology or genetics friends

00:43:54.959 --> 00:44:00.559
in Austria, email them and say, "Have you
ever heard of Julius Bauer?" And they'll probably

00:44:00.559 --> 00:44:01.559
say, "Oh, yeah. Absolutely."

00:44:01.559 --> 00:44:06.650
And the theory was more or less fully accepted
in Europe by 1940. This comes from the 1940

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:12.209
textbook. And the problem was 1940 was a bad
year for Europe. So, the German and Austrian

00:44:12.209 --> 00:44:19.641
medical research communities evaporate. Unlike
in physics, where we, we embraced all the

00:44:19.641 --> 00:44:23.670
European physicists who got chased out of
Europe because we had atomic bombs to build

00:44:23.670 --> 00:44:28.539
and hydrogen bombs and a Cold War to fight.
In medicine and public health, we didn't.

00:44:28.539 --> 00:44:33.869
So Julius Bauer ended up working in Hollywood,
California for the Hospital of Medical Evangelists

00:44:33.869 --> 00:44:38.160
and publishing articles that just said, "Julius
Bauer, Hollywood, California," and nobody

00:44:38.160 --> 00:44:42.880
took his work seriously, although his son
became Dean of the USC Medical School.

00:44:42.880 --> 00:44:48.500
So here's lipophilia in a nutshell. The idea
is lipophilia means 'love of fat'. Okay. The

00:44:48.500 --> 00:44:54.380
way these people saw it, is that some tissues
are more or less predisposed to accumulate

00:44:54.380 --> 00:44:59.239
fat, in the same way that, you can think of
it, we grow hair in some places and not in

00:44:59.239 --> 00:45:00.239
others.

00:45:00.239 --> 00:45:03.579
And we get fat in some place and not in others.
So we don't tend to get fat on our foreheads

00:45:03.579 --> 00:45:09.001
or the back of our hands, but we put in fat
on our guts, under our chins. And so they

00:45:09.001 --> 00:45:13.940
said maybe fat is just like hair. And so,
some people are hairier than others, just

00:45:13.940 --> 00:45:15.720
like some people are fatter than others.

00:45:15.720 --> 00:45:20.140
When men start losing their hair, we don't
accuse them of under eating because they're

00:45:20.140 --> 00:45:23.839
losing weight. We know that there's a lot
of different issues involved.

00:45:23.839 --> 00:45:28.059
So Bauer put it like this. He said, "Like
a malignant tumor or like the fetus, the uterus

00:45:28.059 --> 00:45:33.339
or the breasts of a pregnant woman, the abnormal
lipophilic tissue seizes on foodstuffs, even

00:45:33.339 --> 00:45:37.819
in the case of under nutrition. It maintains
its stock, and may increase it independent

00:45:37.819 --> 00:45:41.779
of the requirements of the organism. A sort
of anarchy exists; the adipose tissue lives

00:45:41.779 --> 00:45:46.359
for itself and does not fit into the precisely
regulated management of the whole organism."

00:45:46.359 --> 00:45:50.900
And this phrase, "even in the case of under
nutrition," begins to tell us why these women

00:45:50.900 --> 00:45:56.299
could get obese in a population where their
children are starving because it didn't matter

00:45:56.299 --> 00:46:01.339
how little food there was. If there was something
driving their accumulation of fat, they were

00:46:01.339 --> 00:46:02.339
gonna get fat anyway.

00:46:02.339 --> 00:46:07.650
So when you look at animal models of obesity,
which you can, what you'll find--what I found--was

00:46:07.650 --> 00:46:14.249
they all fall into two categories. Either,
well, let me just explain. If you have an

00:46:14.249 --> 00:46:19.140
animal model of obesity, how do you want to
test what's driving it, like a genetic model,

00:46:19.140 --> 00:46:26.739
a surgical model. You could lesion the ventromedial
hypothalamus for rat and it'll get obese and

00:46:26.739 --> 00:46:31.420
eat voraciously. So you'll see voracious eating
and obesity. And you wanna know which causes

00:46:31.420 --> 00:46:32.420
which.

00:46:32.420 --> 00:46:38.329
Did this regulation of fat tissue cause what's
called hyperphasia? Or did the hyperphasia

00:46:38.329 --> 00:46:42.719
cause the accumulation of fat? So what you
do, is you just do the experiment and then

00:46:42.719 --> 00:46:46.450
you put the animals on a diet and see whether
they get fat anyway. Okay?

00:46:46.450 --> 00:46:50.479
And what you'll find for every animal model
of obesity is they will get obese anyway,

00:46:50.479 --> 00:46:55.529
even if you put them on a diet. You can, in
some cases, starve them.

00:46:55.529 --> 00:47:00.839
There's a genetic strain of mice that M.R.C.
Greenwood studied in the early 1980s, when

00:47:00.839 --> 00:47:06.309
she put these animals on a diet from the moment
they were weaned and they became more obese.

00:47:06.309 --> 00:47:12.760
They became fatter than their lean control
than their genetic controls, even though they

00:47:12.760 --> 00:47:18.180
were on a diet their whole life. They actually
weighed less. Their organs were smaller. Their

00:47:18.180 --> 00:47:22.329
muscle tissue was smaller and they had more
fat. And in effect, their drive to accumulate

00:47:22.329 --> 00:47:27.900
fat was, in order to do that they cannibalized
their organs and their brain.

00:47:27.900 --> 00:47:34.729
And Jean Meyer, a Tufts nutritionist who played
a large role in this, usually to the detriment

00:47:34.729 --> 00:47:39.829
of society. The way he put it, he studied
a genetic strain of mice. He said, "These

00:47:39.829 --> 00:47:43.559
mice will make fat out of their food under
the most unlikely circumstances, even when

00:47:43.559 --> 00:47:49.219
half-starved." Okay? So it's not that these
mice got fat because they ate too much. They

00:47:49.219 --> 00:47:52.359
got fat if you let them eat anything basically.

00:47:52.359 --> 00:47:56.529
And we're gonna propose, again, that the same
thing's happening in humans. So here's some

00:47:56.529 --> 00:47:59.390
obvious questions. Why vertical growth but
not horizontal?

00:47:59.390 --> 00:48:05.099
When we look at children, we know that overeating
is the effect. Growth is the cause. Why animals

00:48:05.099 --> 00:48:12.690
but not man? An animal's model of obesity,
when you break the gene, you intervene surgically.

00:48:12.690 --> 00:48:18.029
There are even dietary models. What you're
doing is disregulating the fat tissue. You're

00:48:18.029 --> 00:48:19.779
not making the animals eat too much.

00:48:19.779 --> 00:48:24.079
And then the question, if obesity is sort
of excess fat accumulation, what regulates

00:48:24.079 --> 00:48:29.170
fat accumulation? So here's a regulation of
fat. Adiposity 101. If you learn this, you'll

00:48:29.170 --> 00:48:36.480
know more than your doctors do. [pause] By
the way, what gets me is that again, it's

00:48:36.480 --> 00:48:40.719
2011. I lecture in medical schools. I lecture
to obesity research centers.

00:48:40.719 --> 00:48:45.160
And I'm telling them, it's like I'm telling
them something new. I mean, they don't learn

00:48:45.160 --> 00:48:49.910
this in medical school but they forgot it.
But when it comes to the relevance of obesity,

00:48:49.910 --> 00:48:55.349
or why we get fat, the idea that your fat
tissue is regulated and has anything to say

00:48:55.349 --> 00:48:58.180
about this, it's considered radical and quackish.
Okay?

00:48:58.180 --> 00:49:03.789
And the point I'm making is any other growth
problem, like I said, from cancer to height

00:49:03.789 --> 00:49:07.400
to anything, all you're gonna care about is
what hormones, what enzymes, are driving growth.

00:49:07.400 --> 00:49:12.230
So let's care about it here, too. And what
you learn is fat is stored as triglycerides

00:49:12.230 --> 00:49:16.130
in your fat tissue. Here's a triglyceride.
Its three fatty acids bound together by a

00:49:16.130 --> 00:49:22.059
glycerol molecule. Fatty acids are burned
for fuel and the fat enters and exits the

00:49:22.059 --> 00:49:27.650
cell as these fatty acids. And the reason
that is, is because the triglycerides themselves

00:49:27.650 --> 00:49:32.359
are too big to fit in and out of the cell
