They weren't getting -- there wasn't food
industry forcing trans fats on them. So it's

01:21:09.060 --> 01:21:22.450
quite likely, the obvious, again, the null
hypothesis would be the carb content of the

01:21:22.450 --> 01:21:23.450
diet.

01:21:23.450 --> 01:21:25.450
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #2: And then my second
question is, that there are populations that

01:21:25.450 --> 01:21:26.450
tend not to eat meat, like India. There's
so many vegetarians and they get their proteins

01:21:26.450 --> 01:21:27.450
mainly from legumes. So what is your take
on the glycemic index of legumes and other

01:21:27.450 --> 01:21:30.390
non-meat sources of proteins for people who
aren't really eating meat?

01:21:30.390 --> 01:21:34.270
&gt;&gt;Gary Taubes: Well, I do think, again, the
argument I make in the book. The book is called

01:21:34.270 --> 01:21:38.771
'Why We Get Fat'? Not 'How to Lose Weight'.
The reason why I call it 'Why We Get Fat'

01:21:38.771 --> 01:21:42.760
is I wanna make this argument that it’s
literally about the carbs, high glycemic index

01:21:42.760 --> 01:21:48.240
carbs. It doesn't -- the -- legumes are lower
glycemic index. Green vegetables are low glycemic

01:21:48.240 --> 01:21:50.170
index. And the sugars.

01:21:50.170 --> 01:21:56.950
And anyone can improve their diet if they
just remove the sugars and the white flour

01:21:56.950 --> 01:22:00.810
and to some extent, what we call whole wheat
flour in the United States. And actually,

01:22:00.810 --> 01:22:05.890
even one of observations that I wrote about
in 'Good Calories, Bad Calories'.

01:22:05.890 --> 01:22:13.240
As early as 1907 the British Medical Association
had a meeting in which they had a discussion

01:22:13.240 --> 01:22:16.850
about the diabetes problem in India 'cause
diabetes was rampant. They said that it's

01:22:16.850 --> 01:22:22.530
actually worse among the vegetarians sects.
Probably 'cause they were also eating the

01:22:22.530 --> 01:22:25.980
most sugar, which they suggested in 1907.

01:22:25.980 --> 01:22:32.990
But you can improve the diet by removing the
fat and the carbohydrates regardless, is the

01:22:32.990 --> 01:22:39.040
point. But if somebody’s very predisposed
to get fat, if someone's 300 pounds, I would

01:22:39.040 --> 01:22:43.080
argue that you have to get basically, they're
not gonna get enough calories that they.

01:22:43.080 --> 01:22:50.650
The easiest, the way to maximize calories
and minimize carbs is with animal products.

01:22:50.650 --> 01:22:55.630
And so, that's the problem. So if these people,
they could improve on a vegetarian diet. And

01:22:55.630 --> 01:22:59.920
I get emails all the day from people telling
me how much they lost, just giving up sugars.

01:22:59.920 --> 01:23:05.190
I don't think that's enough. In my experience,
I can just ask myself, like, "What would happen

01:23:05.190 --> 01:23:09.340
if I added whole wheat pasta back to my diet?
Maybe three times a week."

01:23:09.340 --> 01:23:13.620
And I could pretty much bet that I'd gain
ten pounds.

01:23:13.620 --> 01:23:18.240
But the point is anyone can lose weight just
by getting rid of, and improve their risk

01:23:18.240 --> 01:23:23.020
profiles, 'cause the argument I make is these
high glycemic index carbs and sugars are the

01:23:23.020 --> 01:23:29.150
cause of the chronic diseases that associate
with obesity and diabetes and insulin resistance.

01:23:29.150 --> 01:23:34.690
So, and then, if it's an all vegetarian or
vegan diet, you're still gonna be better.

01:23:34.690 --> 01:23:38.720
You may not be as lean as you could be if
you threw your ethical considerations to the

01:23:38.720 --> 01:23:44.810
wind and switched to meat, but you will be
healthier than if you keep these foods in

01:23:44.810 --> 01:23:47.340
your diet.

01:23:47.340 --> 01:23:55.470
&gt;&gt;Female Audience Member #3: I was wondering
about people who do a lot of athletics, especially

01:23:55.470 --> 01:23:59.200
like endurance stuff and talk about things
