01:24:52.920 --> 01:24:58.090
The interesting thing, I get a lot of emails
from bike racers, long distance bike racers,

01:24:58.090 --> 01:25:03.910
and mountain bike racers, cause weight is
an issue there. Whereas marathoners, you might

01:25:03.910 --> 01:25:05.280
wanna be as light as possible.

01:25:05.280 --> 01:25:13.350
Or, actually, this is where I get confused.
The evidence suggests you can do just fine

01:25:13.350 --> 01:25:18.310
without any carbs and I actually recommend
-- email me. I'll forward your email to Steve

01:25:18.310 --> 01:25:24.600
Finney. He'll write three thousand words back
in response cause that's what he does.

01:25:24.600 --> 01:25:29.670
But -- and that's a different issue than whether
or not if you carb load like two days before

01:25:29.670 --> 01:25:33.830
the race, you'll do better. Although, I think
Steve would argue that it's not necessary.

01:25:33.830 --> 01:25:38.180
&gt;&gt;Male Audience Member #6: This is a question
about the data. So, in the 1970s, Americans

